      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense regarding tax avoidance, but even with tax evasion, you'd expect to see a trickle of people elsewhere in the county or nearby jurisdictions. These specific pockets are just... silent. No tax records, no land transfers, no church memberships for a whole cluster of people during those years. It's almost like they weren't just hiding; it's like they were entirely unaccounted for by any standard social or political structure of the time. Are there any theories in historical sociology about \"ghost populations\" or groups that might exist entirely outside of the recorded colonial social framework?",
